<HEADING2 item="y">
<Name>Background</Name>
<Ref>background</Ref>
<TEXT_PARA item="y"
line0="{*Topic*}"
line1="&lt;p&gt;{*Text*}&lt;/p&gt;">
<Topic type="Text">Introduction</Topic>
<Text type="Text" html="y" lines="12">Do you have lots of sticky notes lying around with various useful information jotted down? Or many lists of books, movies, links, website logins, personal contacts, or things to do? Can you find them when you need them? Well, I often couldn't. So here's my answer.</Text>
<Ref type="Text" ref="y"></Ref>
</TEXT_PARA>
<TEXT_PARA item="y">
<Topic>Overview</Topic>
<Text>Some would call TreeLine an Outliner, others would call it a PIM. Basically, it just stores almost any kind of information. A tree structure makes it easy to keep things organized. And each node in the tree can contain several fields, forming a mini-database. The output format for each node can be defined, and the output can be shown on the screen, printed, or exported to HTML.</Text>
</TEXT_PARA>
<TEXT_PARA item="y">
<Topic>It's free</Topic>
<Text>Since I'm not in the software business, I'm making this program free for anyone to use, distribute and modify, as long as it is not incorporated into any proprietary programs. If you like the software, feel free to let others know about it. And let me know what you think - see the &lt;a href=&quot;#contact&quot;&gt;Questions, Comments, Criticisms?&lt;/a&gt; section for contact information.</Text>
</TEXT_PARA>
</HEADING2>
<HEADING2 item="y">
<Name>Features</Name>
<Ref>features</Ref>
